an style=\"color:#00B0F0;\"><i><strong>despair.â€™</strong></i></span></p>','images/music/file/74796.mp3',''),(57,2,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>II</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Philosophy of Discernment</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">SaÃ±jaya said, 2.1Â â€˜Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a spoke these words to Arjuna who was overcome with sorrow and despair, his downcast eyes brimming with tears.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 2.2 â€˜Where does this cowardice come from Arjuna, just as we face danger? It does not become a noble warrior like you, nor does it lead to heaven. In fact, it is disgraceful. 2.3 Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, do not be a weakling! This goes against everything a warrior stands for. O terror of your enemies, stand up and stop being such a despicable coward!â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna replied, 2.4 â€˜O demon slayer, how can I oppose BhÄ«á¹£ma and Droá¹‡a in battle? They are worthy of my veneration â€“ not of being slain by my arrows. 2.5 I would rather be a beggar here in this life than kill these great and mighty gurus. How can I enjoy the blood-stained spoils after fighting my teachers over mere wealth? 2.6 And we are not even sure which of the two is preferable: if we should conquer them, or if they should win the battle? Although they are lined up here ready to attack, we would not wish to live after having killed Dhá¹›itarÄá¹£á¹­raâ€™s sons.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â 2.7 My whole being is overcome by pity and weakness.Â My mind is confused. Tell me for sure, which would be better, I implore you, what is my duty? I am your disciple. I will do whatever you command. 2.8 Having obtained unrivalled, prosperous dominion over the entire world or even over the gods, I still do not know what could dispel this grief which is consuming all my faculties.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">SaÃ±jaya</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> said, 2.9 â€˜After all this Arjuna</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> said to Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, â€˜I shall not fight.â€™ and fell silent. Â 2.10 O Dhá¹›itarÄá¹£á¹­ra, descendant of Bharata, there between the two armies Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a smiled as he addressed the dejected Arjuna with these words.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 2.11 â€˜You grieve for those for whom no grief is due and yet you sound wise. But the wise grieve neither for the living nor the dead.Â 2.12 Indeed, there was never a time when I did not exist, nor you, nor these rulers of men; and none of us will ever cease to exist. 2.13 Just as this body passes through childhood, adulthood and old age, so do embodied beings acquire another body.</span><a href=\"#_ftn4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> The wise are not deluded about this. 2.14 O son of KuntÄ«, physical sensations cause only heat and cold, pleasure and pain. They come and go, they are impermanent. You must endure them, O descendant of Bharata. 2.15 Only the wise are ready for immortality. O Lion among men, happiness and misery are the same for them, they are not troubled by this pair of opposites.Â 2.16 The unreal has no existence. That which exists never ceases to be.</span><a href=\"#_ftn5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Sages perceive the truth about both of these. 2.17 Know that which pervades all this to be indestructible. Nothing can cause the dissolution of the unmanifest. 2.18 The Self within is eternal, indestructible and immeasurable, but these bodies will come to an end; therefore fight, O descendent of Bharata!Â Â 2.19 Whoever imagines this Self to be a killer or who thinks of It as getting killed, neither one understands that Spirit does not kill nor is It killed. 2.20 Consciousness is not born nor does It ever die; in fact, having existed It will never cease to be. As It is birthless, eternal, omnipresent and primeval, It is not slain when the body is slain. 2.21 O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, how can that man kill when he knows the Self is indestructible, eternal, birthless and imperishable? Whom does he kill? 2.22 Just as one gets new clothes having thrown away old ones, so, after leaving behind worn-out bodies, the embodied Self takes on new ones. 2.23 Weapons do not pierce this Self, fire does not burn It, water does not wet It nor does the wind dry It. 2.24 Consciousness cannot be pierced, burnt, wetted or dried. It is eternal, all-pervading, stable. It is unmoving and everlasting. 2.25 It is said to be unmanifest, unthinkable and unchanging. Therefore, there is no need to grieve when you know this. 2.26 And even if you think of it as continually being born or continually dying, you should still not grieve, O Arjuna. 2.27 Death is certain for whatever is born, and for the dead birth is assured. Â So why would you grieve when the outcome is inevitable? 2.28 In the beginning all creatures are unmanifest, in the middle they manifest, and in the end, they become unmanifest again. O descendant of Bharata, why complain about the inevitable? 2.29 Some see It as miraculous; others declare It to be miraculous, yet others hear of It as miraculous; but even after hearing about It, no-one knows It. 2.30 This Self is ever unharmed within any embodiment. That is why you should not grieve for any creature, Arjuna. 2.31 And with regards to your own duty, you should not be troubled either. Indeed, for a warrior there is nothing greater than a righteous battle. 2.32 O Arjuna, happy are the warriors who reach the open gate of heaven, having the good fortune to fight in a battle like this. 2.33 Now if you do not take part in this just war, having disregarded your own duty and reputation, you will be committing a crime. 2.34 People will also speak of your unending disgrace. And for people who are respected, infamy is much worse than death. 2.35 The great warriors will think you have withdrawn from this battle out of fear. And some who held you in high esteem will then belittle you. 2.36 And your enemies will say many slanderous things, ridiculing your prowess. What could cause greater anguish than that? 2.37 Either you will be killed and attain heaven or, having won the war, you will enjoy rulership over the earth. Therefore, stand up, O son of KuntÄ«, resolved to fight. 2.38 So, engage in battle, indifferent to pleasure or pain, gain or loss, victory or defeat! In this way you will do no wrong. 2.39 Arjuna, listen to me! If you exercise reason together with determination you will avoid the binding aspect of action, according to SÄá¹…khya philosophy. 2.40 On this path no effort is wasted, nor is there a loss of progress. By even a little of such honest living, you are protected from great danger. 2.41 O descendant of the Kuru clan, the resolve of those who are awake is of a single nature, whereasÂ the thoughts of the irresolute take them endlessly in multiple directions. 2.42 Ignorant people make flowery speeches, Arjuna. They revel in Vedic utterances, saying, \"There is nothing more</span><a href=\"#_ftn6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">.\" 2.43 Overtaken by desire, intent on gaining heaven through the results of action and rebirth, they perform many specific rites aimed at achieving pleasure and power. 2.44 Carried away by thoughts of rituals, attached to pleasure and power, they are not granted the peace of the Self through a resolute mind. 2.45 The Vedas speak of the three guá¹‡as</span><a href=\"#_ftn7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. Be free of the three guá¹‡as, Arjuna. Be indifferent to the pairs of opposites. Satisfied in the self, always remain in sattva, without a need for acquisition or security. 2.46 For one who knows Brahman, all the Vedas are as of much value as a well surrounded by water during a flood. 2.47 Your concern should be with actions alone and never with the results. The aim should not be the outcome of action; but let there be no attachment to doing nothing either. 2.48 Perform your actions established in yoga</span><a href=\"#_ftn8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, O Conqueror of Wealth,Â having let go of attachments and having become indifferent to success and failure. Such equanimity is called yoga. 2.49 Activity is far inferior to the yoga of reason, O Conqueror of Wealth. Seek refuge in reason! Pitiable indeed are result-oriented people. 2.50 Therefore, devote yourself to yoga! Yoga is skill in action. With balanced judgment, both good and bad actions are at once abandoned. 2.51 Through balanced judgment, the wise let go the results of action and are freed from the bondage of rebirth. They travel a path that is free from pain. 2.52 When your mind traverses the mire of delusion, then you will become completely indifferent to what has been heard and what there is to hear. 2.53 Now your reason is bewildered by Vedic doctrines. When it is established, immovable in deep meditation, then you will experience unity.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna asked, 2.54 â€˜O Demon Slayer, what is the description of someone of steady wisdom, who is focussed in meditation and whose intelligence is unwavering? How might he speak, sit and move?â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 2.55 â€˜O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, when he lets go of all the desires in his heart, satisfied in Himself alone, content by Himself, then he is said to be one of steady wisdom.Â 2.56Â Someone whose mind is calm, unagitated in adversity and unaffected by pleasure, who is free from attachment, fear and anger, is called an earnest seeker of steady wisdom. 2.57 Someone established in wisdom is always detached - whatever he meets, be it good or bad, he neither loves nor hates it. 2.58 And just as the tortoise withdraws its limbs from all sides, so he withdraws his senses from sense-objects and is established in wisdom. 2.59 The sensual world turns away from self-restrained people, but their taste for it lingers on. Only on seeing the Supreme do they also lose interest in the taste. 2.60Â O Son of KuntÄ«, even for someone who is striving for wisdom the mind is forcibly carried away by the tortuous senses!Â Â 2.61 He should sit intent on me, disciplined, restraining them all. He is only established in wisdom when he has learnt to control his senses. 2.62 When a person dwells on sense objects</span><a href=\"#_ftn9\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[9]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> an attachment for them arises. From attachment comes desire and desire leads to frustration and anger. 2.63 From anger comes delusion; due to delusion memory starts fading; when memory has been lost, the capacity to reason is destroyed and once reason is gone there is total destruction. 2.64 But a self-controlled person, restraining his senses attains peace, moving among objects free from likes or dislikes. 2.65Â Once at peace, all oneâ€™s miseries are left behind. When the mind is serene oneâ€™s judgment is instantly improved. 2.66 Distracted people cannot be reasonable. Also, the undisciplined do not have the ability to focus. Without concentration, there can be no peace. And without peace where will happiness come from?Â Â 2.67 The mind, when led astray by the roaming senses, is robbed of understanding, just as a ship at sea is tossed about by the wind.2.68 Therefore, O Arjuna, his wisdom is steady whose senses are completely detached from sense objects. 2.69 In what is night for all beings, the self-controlled are awake. And what keeps other beings awake, is night for the sage who sees clearly. 2.70Â As the ocean remains the same although rivers flow into and fill it, so the wise obtain peace, although flooded by desires from all sides; not so for someone full of cravings.Â 2.71 Having given up all desires, a man can move around without cravings, without a sense of â€˜mineâ€™, without ego. He attains peace. 2.72 O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, on attaining this highest state, he is never deluded. Established here, even in his final hour, he attains oneness with Brahman.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> SaÃ±jaya is still speaking to Dhá¹›itarÄá¹£á¹­ra.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> <i>Conqueror of sleep = Arjuna.Â </i>In some cases, the names Arjuna and <i>Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a</i> have been used rather than the epithet to avoid confusion.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> <i>Lord of the senses = Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a</i></span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> What we call death is just another phase of life.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> The word â€˜unrealâ€™ can easily be misconstrued as absolutely non-existent (like a barren womanâ€™s son), but here â€˜unrealâ€™ should be understood to be an order of existence between total reality and absolute unreality i.e. â€˜relative realityâ€™. It has existence but is dependent, changeable and temporary. â€˜Existenceâ€™ here refers to independent or absolute being. It has no cause, is independent and unchanging over time. The analogy of water and waves can explain this. Water represents â€˜that which existsâ€™. Waves represent the â€˜unrealâ€™ since their existence depends entirely on water, whereas water can exist without waves.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â These people interpret the Vedas as containing nothing more than rituals that promise heaven, cattle, wealth and the like.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Sattva, rajas and tamas are the three states of consciousness. Just as light is emitted, reflected and absorbed, so sattva, rajas and tamas can be explained in terms of emitting, reflecting and absorbing consciousness, as it were. See chapters 15, 17 and 18 especially.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Yoga is a way of life that brings about unity. It is an experience of uninterrupted peace, certainty and bliss. The aim of yoga is to rest in this unity regardless of the circumstances we face. When the â€˜yoga of reasonâ€™ is mentioned in the next verse it implies achieving this state by discerning between the changing and the changeless.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><a href=\"#_ftnref9\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[9]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> The world around us is made up of sense objects. Usually, we react to them in accordance with our past experiences, either getting attracted or repulsed mentally and emotionally. This process is the cause of stress and prevents us from relaxing in the peace of the Self. Ultimately, no matter what the sensual world presents to our senses, we can remain balanced and touch nothing.</span></p>','images/music/file/640801270.mp3',''),(58,7,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>VII</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>Lower and Higher Knowledge</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord spoke, 7.1 â€˜With mind intent on Me, O Son ofÂ Pá¹›ithÄ, practising yoga and finding refuge in Me, hear how you shall undoubtedly know Me in full. 7.2 I shall fully teach you this knowledge combined with experience which, being known, nothing more besides here remains to be known. 7.3 Among thousands of men, perchance one strives for perfection; even among those who strive and are perfect, only one perchance knows Me in truth. 7.4 â€˜Earth, water, fire, air, space, mind, reason and egoâ€™; thus is My praká¹›iti divided eightfold. 7.5 All this is My inferior nature, but as distinct from this, know My superior nature, the very life, O Mighty-armed, by which this universe is upheld. 7.6 Know that all beings have their birth in these. I am the source and dissolution of the whole universe. 7.7 There is nothing else higher than Me, O Arjuna</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. In Me all this is woven as clusters of gems on a string. 7.8 I am the sapidity in water, O Son of KuntÄ«, I am the light in the moon and the sun, I am the syllable à¥ in all the Vedas, sound in ether, humanity in man. 7.9 And I am the agreeable odour in the earth, the brilliance in fire, Â the vitality in all beings. I am the austerity in ascetics. 7.10 Know Me, O Son ofÂ Pá¹›ithÄ, as the eternal seed of all beings; I am the intelligence of the intelligent and the splendour of the radiant. 7.11 I am the power of the mighty, devoid of passion and attachment. In beings, I am that desire which is not unlawful, O Bull of theÂ Bharatas.Â 7.12 Know that thoseÂ sÄttvika, rÄjasika and tÄmasika states arise only from Me. Though I am not in them, they are in Me. 7.13 This whole universe is composed of these threeÂ guá¹‡as. Â Those who do not recognize that I am immutable and beyond these, are deluded. 7.14Â Divine indeed is this universe made of the threeÂ guá¹‡as. My illusion is difficult to penetrate, only those who resort to Me transcend this illusion. 7.15 Deluded wrongdoers do not take refuge in Me. Ignorant of this illusion, these lowest of men partake of a demonic existence. 7.16 Arjuna, four types of benevolent people worship Me: the afflicted, those desirous of knowledge, those seeking wealth and men of wisdom. 7.17 Ever steadfast and devoted only to the One, the man of wisdom stands out among these. I am exceedingly dear to him as is he to Me.Â 7.18 In fact all of them are noble, but the man of wisdom is considered to be My very Self. His mind is steadfast, abiding in Me, the unsurpassed goal.Â 7.19 After many births the man of wisdom takes refuge in Me, realising thatÂ Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> is all. Such a great soul is very hard to find. 7.20 But those whose understanding is undermined by a multitude of desires resort to other gods, following this or that religious practice, bound by their own habitual nature. 7.21 I grant unshakeable faith to any disciple who wishes to worship Me devotedly in any form. 7.22 Endowed with such faith he seeks to worship Me in any form and hence fulfils those desires, which I myself have ordained. 7.23 However, for petty-minded people their results are short-lived. Just as My devotees come unto Me, these worshippers of the gods go to their gods.Â 7.24 Not knowing My Higher Being to be unchanging, unsurpassed and unmanifest, the unintelligent think of Me as having entered into manifestation. 7.25 Shrouded and immersed in illusion I am not visible to all. Deluded people do not recognize Me as birthless and immutable. 7.26 I know the living and the dead, as well as beings that are yet to exist, O Arjuna, but no one knows Me.Â 7.27 O Arjuna, descendant ofÂ Bharata, all beings are subject to illusion at birth, confused by the pairs of opposites which spring from desire and aversion.Â Â 7.28 But virtuous people, whose bad habits are spent, worship Me with firm resolve free from the delusion of pairs of opposites. 7.29 Striving to escape from old age and death, they take refuge in Me. They fully comprehend that Brahman, their innermost Self, as well as all activity. 7.30 Those who know Me as the supreme being, the supreme divinity, as well as the basis of sacrifice, really understand Me.Â  Their minds are steadfast, even at the hour of death.â€™</span></p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Conqueror of wealth</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> VÄsudeva is another name forÂ Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a.</span></p>','images/music/file/481542313.mp3',''),(59,8,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>VIII</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Indestructible Brahman</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna asked, 8.1 â€˜What is this Brahman? What is the individual self? What is action, O Supreme One? What is the physical world really and what is meant by the divine realm? 8.2 O Slayer of Madhu, who is the sacrificer</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> and how does he operate here in this body? And how are You known by the self-controlled at the hour of death?â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord answered, 8.3 â€˜Brahman is indestructible and supreme. Â Every individual is said to be of the nature of Brahman. Action is known as the creative power which causes the birth of creatures. 8.4 The physical world is impermanent by nature and its source is the power of the divine. Â I alone am the Sacrificer</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> here in this body, O best of men. 8.5 And whoever remembers Me at the final hour of departure he comes to My realm after leaving his corpse behind. Of that, there is no doubt. Â 8.6 O Son of KuntÄ«, whatever state of being they bring to mind as they are leaving this corpse, they reach that very same state, always becoming that. 8.7 Therefore, remember Me at all times and fight! With your mind and heart fixed on Me you will undoubtedly come to Me. 8.8 With the mind engaged in the practice of Yoga, never turning to anything else, meditating, one goes to the divine supreme Spirit, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ. 8.9 One should remember the ancient seers and the sovereign supporter of all things whose form is unimaginable, subtler than an atom and radiant like a sun which is beyond darkness.Â 8.10Â Having made the vital breath enter properly between the eyebrows, strengthened by Yoga with the mind at rest and full of devotion, one attains that divine supreme Spirit at the hour of death. 8.11 I will briefly explain that path which Vedic scholars call indestructible and for which, desiring to tread it, ascetics follow a life of chastity free from passion. 8.12 Controlling all the gates</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> of the body and turning the mind toward the heart, placing oneâ€™s own vital breath on the crown of the head, fixed in Yogic concentration, 8.13 uttering the single syllable â€˜à¥â€™ as representing Brahman, he meditates on Me. On his departure, he leaves this body behind and goes to the supreme goal. 8.14 O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, I am easy to reach for the Yogin who always remembers Me, who is constantly single-minded and ever-devoted.Â 8.15 Great souls who have achieved supreme perfection approach Me. They no longer suffer rebirth into this transient place of misery. 8.16 All the worlds, including the Creators realm, are subject to continual regeneration, but he who approaches Me is not reborn, O Son of KuntÄ«. 8.17 Those who know that a cosmic day</span><a href=\"#_ftn4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> extends for a thousand yugas and that a cosmic night ends after a thousand yugas, such people know about cosmic day and night. 8.18 At the dawn of a cosmic day all manifestations emerge from the unmanifest</span><a href=\"#_ftn5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. On the arrival of a cosmic night, they dissolve back into the so-called unmanifest. 8.19 Inevitably, O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, all these beings are reabsorbed on the arrival of a cosmic night and they reappear at the start of the next cosmic day, being born again and again. 8.20 But beyond this is another unmanifest realm, unmanifest beyond time, which alone does not perish when all beings perish. 8.21 It is said that this unmanifest is indestructible, that it is the ultimate goal, on reaching which there is no return. That is My supreme home. 8.22 O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, that Supreme Spirit in whom all beings are established and by whom all this is pervaded, is attainable by single-pointed devotion. 8.23 Now I will speak about that moment of departure when yogis die and either never come back or actually do return, O Bull of theÂ Bharatas. 8.24 For people departing in daylight, with the sacrificial fire during the bright lunar fortnight and the six months of the northern course of the sun; knowing Brahman they go to Brahman.Â 8.25 But a yogin returns here when he reaches the lunar light at night with sacrificial smoke, during the dark lunar fortnight and the six months of the southern course of the sun. 8.26 These are the two paths of the world deemed to be inevitable, the bright one and the dark one. On one path, he goes never to return, with the other he comes back again. 8.27 O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, the yogin who knows these two paths is never confused. For this reason, apply yourself to yoga at all times.Â 8.28 Knowing all this the yogin transcends merits gained from studying the Vedas, making offerings and gifts and following disciplines. He reaches that supreme and primal state.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> This is explained in verse 4.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> The Sacrificer is Viá¹£á¹‡u, as explained in the Åšaá¹‡karaâ€™s commentary. Viá¹£á¹‡u means â€˜He who lives everywhereâ€™ (as an embodied being), which is a way of saying the ParamÄtman. As all actions are dedicated to some power like wealth, fame, offspring and so on, these may become traps that ensnare us in the world. The only way to live and act, but remain unbound is to dedicate, offer up, surrender or sacrifice every action to the ultimate power, the ParamÄtman.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Refers to the body with two eyes, ears and nostrils, a mouth and the organs of evacuation and generation. cf. 5.13</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> A kalpa or cosmic day is 1000 great yugas. One great yuga is 4,320,000 years divided into four ages: 1,728,000 solar years for a Satyuga (Golden Age), 1,296,000 years for a TretÄyuga (Silver Age), 864,000 years for a DvÄparayuga (Bronze Age) and 432,000 years for a Kaliyuga (Iron Age). A cosmic night also lasts for one kalpa. There are 360 cosmic days in a cosmic year and the Creatorâ€™s lifespan is 120 cosmic years or 373,248 billion solar years. This current Kaliyuga started on the day this battle was finished, 18 days after this conversation between Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a and Arjuna on 18 February 3,102 B.C. So over 5,100 years ago.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> This unmanifest â€˜storehouseâ€™ where latent impressions are kept and from where they emerge at the next cycle of creation is different from the unmanifest, unchanging consciousness.</span></p>','images/music/file/424183844.mp3',''),(60,9,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>IX</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>Royal Knowledge and Royal Secret</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord spoke, 9.1 â€˜Because you are without malice, I will tell you this most secret knowledge which, once understood and combined with experience, will free you from impurities. 9.2 This most important knowledge, the sovereign secret, is the supreme purifier. It is readily understandable, lawful, easy to implement and unchanging.Â  9.3Â O terror of your enemies, people who do not put faith in this knowledge do not reach Me and are born again and again on the path of death and transmigration. 9.4Â This whole universe is pervaded by Me, yet My form is not seen. All beings have their existence in Me, but I do not exist because of them.Â 9.5Â Nor do beings support Me, I uphold them. Behold my lordly origin! They do not sustain Me, Myself being the support. 9.6Â As the all-pervading air while moving everywhere always exists in space, so all beings exist in Me. Reflect on this!Â 9.7Â All beings, O son of KuntÄ«, return to My nature at the end of a cosmic</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> day. At the beginning of the next cosmic day, I send them forth again.Â 9.8Â Supported by My own nature, I create this entire multitude of beings over and over again. They are powerless, driven by nature. 9.9Â But such actions do not bind Me, O conqueror of wealth, since I remain indifferent and unattached to these actions. 9.10Â Under My supervision nature produces the moving and the unmoving. Because of this, O son of KuntÄ«, the universe keeps revolving.Â Â 9.11Â The ignorant treat Me with contempt because I am clad in human form. They do not know My higher nature, that I am the great Lord of beings. 9.12Â They are devoid of sense, with vain hopes, useless actions, insignificant knowledge, clinging to the delusion of a fiendish and demonic nature. 9.13Â But great souls worship Me wholeheartedly, O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, resorting to their divine nature and knowing Me as the unchanging source of all beings.9.14Â Ever steadfast, they worship Me with devotion, constantly celebrating and honouring Me and striving with firm vows.9.15Â Yet others worship Me by dedicating self-knowledge, venerating Me either as the One or as distinct and diverse within every form. 9.16Â I am the ritual, I am the sacrifice, I am the offering, I am the medicinal herb, I am the sacred text, I am also the clarified butter, I am the fire and I am the pouring of the offering.</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â 9.17Â I am the father of this universe, its mother, the founder, the grandfather, the One to be known. I am the sacred syllable à¥, theÂ á¹šik,Â SÄmaÂ as well as Yajur Veda. 9.18Â I am the goal, the supporter, the great Lord, the witness, the abode, the refuge, the friend, the origin, the dissolution and the foundation, the treasure house and the indestructible seed. 9.19Â O Arjuna, I radiate heat, I withhold and send forth rain and I am both immortality and death, the real and the unreal.Â 9.20 Scholars of the three Vedas, Soma drinkers and souls purified from evil, all worship Me with sacrificial offerings, heaven-bound. They approach the pure world of the Lord of the gods and enjoy the gods celestial delights in heaven. 9.21Â Having enjoyed the vast world of heaven, their merit exhausted, they enter the mortal world. Thus, because they crave enjoyments, they succeed in going there and returning</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, conforming to the threefold law. 9.22Â I bring abundance and security to those people who honour Me, reflecting on Me as non-different, constantly united in Yoga. 9.23Â Even faithful devotees of other gods in fact worship Me, though they do not worship according to the rules, O Son of KuntÄ«. 9.24Â They deviate and fall because they do not recognise Me in truth, as I alone am the enjoyer and the Lord of all sacrifices. 9.25Â Worshippers of gods go to gods, those devoted to ancestors go to ancestors, spirit-devotees go to spirits. So also, those who worship Me come to Me.9.26Â Whoever devotedly offers Me a leaf, a flower, some fruit or water, I accept this offering of devotion from that pure soul. 9.27Â Whatever you do, whatever you eat, whatever you sacrifice, whatever you give, whatever discipline you practice, O Son of KuntÄ«, do that as an offering to Me. 9.28Â You will certainly be freed from the bonds of actions which produce good and bad results, with your mind disciplined by the yoga of renunciation, liberated you will come to Me. 9.29Â I am the same consciousness in all beings; none are disliked nor dear to Me. But those who worship Me with devotion are in Me, and I am also in them. 9.30Â If a man worships Me with undivided attention, even if wicked he is deemed to be righteous because his intention is pure.Â 9.31Â Soon he becomes virtuous and attains everlasting peace. O Son of KuntÄ«, know that no devotee of Mine is ever lost. 9.32Â O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, those who take refuge in Me, even if they may have a tainted birth: Â women, traders andÂ labourers,Â even they attain the highest goal; 9.33Â how much more then holy Brahma-seekers and devoted royal Sages! Having reached this transient, joyless world you should worship Me. 9.34Â Fix your mind on Me, be devoted and dedicate to Me and revere Me. With Me as the supreme goal, thus steadfast you will come to Me, the Self.â€™</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> cf. Chapter 8 verse 17</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â In many rituals, ghee is poured into the fire as an offering to the gods. See 4.24.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> going to heaven and returning to earth</span></p>','images/music/file/478790840.mp3',''),(61,10,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>X</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Yoga of Divine Manifestation.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord spoke: 10.1 â€˜O Arjuna</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, listen to My exalted words which I will speak because of my affection for you and from a desire for your welfare. 10.2 Neither the multitude of gods nor great sages know My origin. In every way, I am the source of the gods and the great sages. 10.3 He who knows Me as unborn and beginningless, the Mighty Lord of the world, is enlightened among mortals. He is released from all evils. 10.4 Intelligence, knowledge, a lack of delusion, patience, truth, self-restraint, tranquillity, pleasure and pain, birth, death, fear and fearlessness, 10.5 non-violence, impartiality, contentment, discipline, charity, fame and disrepute: all these manifold conditions of beings arise from Me. 10.6 The seven great sages, the four ancient ones and also the fourteen Manus, originating in Me, were born from My mind. From them came all these worldly creatures. 10.7 He who knows the essence of My divine manifestation is united with Me by unwavering yoga. Of this there is no doubt. 10.8 I am the source of all. From Me everything evolves. Contemplative by nature, reflecting thus, the wise worship Me. 10.9 Thinking of Me, dedicating their lives to Me, they speak of Me, constantly enlightening each other. They are contented and delighted. 10.10 On those who worship Me with affection, constantly connected, I bestow that union through the intellect by which they come to Me. 10.11 I dwell within their own being and just out of sympathy for them do I destroy the darkness born of ignorance with the radiant light of knowledge.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 10.12 â€˜You are the supreme Brahman, the supreme abode, the supreme purifier, the eternal divine Spirit, the primal, unborn and all-pervading God. 10.13 All sages have said this about You, including the divine sage NÄrada,</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Asita Devala</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> and VyÄsa</span><a href=\"#_ftn4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. Now You Yourself tell me the same. 10.14Â O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, I believe all this that You are telling me to be true. O Blessed One, it is true that neither gods nor demons know Your manifestation.Â 10.15Â O Supreme Being! You alone know Yourself by Yourself. The Provider of all beings, Lord of beings, God of gods, O Lord of the universe, 10.16 please describe fully those divine manifestations through which You display Yourself, pervading these worlds. 10.17 Constantly contemplating You, how may I know You, O Yogin</span><a href=\"#_ftn5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">? And in what various aspects are You to be thought of by me, O Lord? 10.18 Tell me more, in detail, about Your power and divine manifestation, O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a. I cannot hear enough about your immortality.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord spoke, 10.19 â€˜Listen, O Best of the Kurus. I will tell you about My own divine manifestations, but only the most prominent ones, for there is no limit to My diversity. 10.20 I am the Self, O Arjuna, abiding in the heart of all beings. I am their beginning as well as their middle and their end. 10.21 Out the Ä€dityas</span><a href=\"#_ftn6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, I am Viá¹£á¹‡u; among stars, the radiant sun. I am MarÄ«chi of the Maruts</span><a href=\"#_ftn7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. Among the planets, I am the moon. 10.22 Out of the Vedas, I am the SÄma Veda. I am VÄsava</span><a href=\"#_ftn8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> among the gods. With regard to the senses, I am the interpreting mind. I am the consciousness in beings. 10.23 And of the Rudras, I am Åšiva. I am Kubera</span><a href=\"#_ftn9\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[9]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> of the Yaká¹£as and RÄká¹£asas. Among the Vasus</span><a href=\"#_ftn10\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[10]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, I am fire and among the mountains, Meru. 10.24Â O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ, know that I am Bá¹›ihaspati, the chief teacher of the gods. Among army generals, I am Skanda. Among water bodies, I am the ocean. 10.25 Of the great sages, I am Bhá¹›igu. In speech, I am the single syllableÂ à¥. Â Of sacrifices, I am the whispered mantra. Among immovable things, the HimÄlayas. 10.26 Among all trees, I am the Peepul tree; and among divine sages, I am NÄrada. Of the Gandharvas, Chitraratha; of perfected sages, the sage Kapila. 10.27 Know that among horses, I am Indraâ€™s divine steed who was born from the nectar of immortality. Of lordly elephants, I am AirÄvata</span><a href=\"#_ftn11\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[11]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">; and the king of men. 10.28 Of weapons, I am the thunderbolt and among cows, I am the wish-fulfilling cow</span><a href=\"#_ftn12\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[12]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. I am the progenitor Kandarpa</span><a href=\"#_ftn13\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[13]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, and of serpents, I am VÄsuki. 10.29 I am Ananta among the NÄgas</span><a href=\"#_ftn14\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[14]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. I am Varuá¹‡a</span><a href=\"#_ftn15\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[15]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> among water creatures. Of ancestors, I am Aryaman</span><a href=\"#_ftn16\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[16]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> and among the controllers, I am Yama</span><a href=\"#_ftn17\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[17]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">.Â 10.30Â I am PrahlÄda</span><a href=\"#_ftn18\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[18]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> among the demons; and I am the measurer of time. Among beasts, I am the lion; and among birds, I am Garuda</span><a href=\"#_ftn19\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[19]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. 10.31 Of purifiers, I am the wind. I am RÄma among warriors. Â Among sea monsters, I am the alligator; and I am the Ganges among rivers. 10.32 O Arjuna, I am the beginning and the end of creations, as well as everything in between. Of all knowledge, I am the knowledge of the supreme Self; and the dialectic of debaters. 10.33 Of letters, I am the sound A; and the dvandva</span><a href=\"#_ftn20\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[20]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> among compound words. I alone am infinite time. I am the Creator, facing in all directions. 10.34 I am all-destroying death and the origin of what is to be. Among feminine qualities, I am fame, prosperity, speech, memory, intelligence, courage and patience.Â 10.35Â Of chants, I am the Bá¹›ihatsÄman; among metres, I am the GÄyatrÄ«. Of months, the MÄrgaÅ›Ä«rá¹£a</span><a href=\"#_ftn21\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[21]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">; and of the seasons, spring abounding with blossoms. 10.36 I am the gambling of cheaters and the radiance of splendour. I am victory, I am effort, I am the goodness of sattva. 10.37 Among the Vá¹›iá¹£á¹‡is,</span><a href=\"#_ftn22\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[22]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> I am VÄsudeva; among the sons of Pandu, Arjuna. I am VyÄsa</span><a href=\"#_ftn23\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[23]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> among the sages and UÅ›anÄ</span><a href=\"#_ftn24\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[24]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> among poets. 10.38 In punishment, I am the rod</span><a href=\"#_ftn25\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[25]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. I am the guidance of those desiring victory. Of secrets, I am silence; and I am the knowledge of the wise. 10.39 And Arjuna, I am also that which is the seed of all creatures. There is nothing that exists, moving or unmoving, which does not exist through Me. 10.40 There is no end to My divine manifestations, O scorcher of foes. However, I have described all this to illustrate the extent of My divine manifestation. 10.41 Understand that whatever manifest being is glorious or vigorous, it is sustained by only a fraction of My splendour. 10.42 But of what use is this extensive but incomplete knowledge to you, Arjuna? I support this entire universe constantly with only a single fragment of Myself.â€™</span></p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">of strong armsÂ </span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Son of the four-faced BrahmÄ.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Father of Devala, a sage.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The author of this work, the MahÄbhÄrata.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a has accomplished many actions in this human form, but without getting attached to them. This makes him a Yogin.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">These are a group of 12 gods or powers, which live in our body.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">There are 47 Maruts who oversee everything with regard to the universal element of air in the creation.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Another name for Indra, the Lord of the gods.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref9\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[9]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â Kubera is in charge of wealth. (But it isÂ not always gained lawfullyÂ because he is a power associated withÂ Yaká¹£as and RÄká¹£asas.)</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref10\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[10]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> A group of 8 bright gods.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref11\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[11]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The name of Indraâ€™s celestial elephant.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref12\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[12]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">See 3.10</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref13\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[13]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> KÄmadeva Son of Viá¹£á¹‡u, god of desire.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref14\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[14]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The celestial snake on which Lord Viá¹£á¹‡u reclines.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref15\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[15]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Deity presiding over the oceans.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref16\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[16]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Deity presiding over the sun and the eye.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref17\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[17]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Yama is the god of death, the ultimate controller.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref18\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[18]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">PrahlÄda, although the son of the king of the demons, was a devotee of Viá¹£á¹‡u. Eventually, an incarnation of Viá¹£á¹‡u killed the king.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref19\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[19]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Eagle deity and vehicle of Viá¹£á¹‡u, protector of the law.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref20\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[20]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â In Sanskrit grammar, there are different categories of compound words, one of which is a list, called <i>dvandva</i>.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref21\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[21]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> December as the tenth month.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref22\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[22]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â the dynasty thatÂ Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a was born into. He was named VÄsudeva by his family.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref23\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[23]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â The author of this work.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref24\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[24]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â An ancestral king fromÂ Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡aâ€™s dynasty.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref25\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[25]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Literally, a stick, representing any instrument for punishment.</span></p>','images/music/file/833844783.mp3',''),(62,11,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XI</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Vision of the Universal Form.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 11.1 â€˜As a favour to me You have spoken about the ultimate secret, known as the supreme Self. With this, my delusion has been dissolved. 11.2 I have heard from You in detail about the origin and dissolution of all beings, O Lotus-eyed One, as well as about Your imperishable, great Self. 11.3 O Supreme Lord, O magnificent Spirit, as You have described Yourself, now I wish to see Your majestic form. 11.4 If You think it is possible for me to see that O Lord, then show me Your imperishable Self, O Prince of Yogins.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 11.5 â€˜Behold My forms in a variety of divine representations and of multifarious colours and shapes, O Arjuna! They are a hundredfold, or rather a thousand-fold. 11.6 Look at so many wonders never seen before, Arjuna! Behold Ä€dityas, Vasus, Rudras, the AÅ›vin twins and Maruts too. 11.7 See the entire universe now, O Arjuna, with the animate and the inanimate standing together, here in My body, and whatever else you wish to see. 11.8 But you cannot see Me with your own eyes, therefore, I give you a divine eye. Behold My yogic power!â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">SaÃ±jaya said, 11.9 â€˜O king, having spoken thus,Â Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, the great yogic master, revealed His majestic and supreme form for Arjunaâ€™s sake. 11.10 He had a multitude of wondrous displays with many mouths and eyes, and numerous divine ornaments, holding up a myriad of divine weapons. 11.11 He wore divine garlands and garments with heavenly perfumes and ointments. The infinite, perfect and miraculous Lord was facing in all directions. 11.12 If a thousand suns should rise all at once in the sky, such splendour would be like the radiance of that great Being. 11.13 Then Arjuna saw the entire universe placed there in the body of the God of gods, as one, though divided into many groups. 11.14 Arjuna was struck with such amazement that his hair stood on end. Making a gesture of reverence, he bowed his head to the Lord and spoke.â€™ 11.15 â€˜O Deity, I see the divine powers in Your body, as well as all kinds of beings assembled there. Lord BrahmÄ seated on his lotus and all the sages and divine serpents. 11.16 I see You everywhere, infinite in form, with many arms, bellies, faces and eyes. I cannot even see where You begin or end, or where Your centre is. O Lord of all, your form is the whole universe. 11.17 I see You crowned, armed with a club and bearing a discus, a mass of splendour shining on all sides with the immeasurable radiance of many suns, a blazing fire difficult to behold. 11.18 I truly believe You are the unchanging, the supreme aim of knowledge. You are the ultimate resting place of all, the imperishable defender of the eternal law. You are the primordial Spirit. 11.19 I see You as infinite power, without a beginning, middle or end, with innumerable arms and the moon and the sun as Your eyes, a fire blazing from Your mouth burning this whole world with Your own radiance. 11.20 This space between heaven and earth is pervaded by You alone in all directions.Â  O Great Being, the three worlds</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> tremble as they see this wondrous and terrifying form of Yours. 11.21 Throngs of deities enter into You with reverent gestures, some terrified, others singing praises. Crowds of great sages and perfected ones extol You with resounding adoration, saying \"Hail!\"Â 11.22 Rudras, Ä€dityas, Vasus, SÄdhyas, ViÅ›ve gods, AÅ›vin twins, Maruts and Uá¹£mapas, hordes of Gandharvas, Yaká¹£as, Asuras and sages with powers all behold You in utter amazement. 11.23 O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, upon seeing Your great form with innumerable mouths and eyes, with many arms, thighs and feet, with multiple bellies and countless formidable tusks and gaping mouths, the worlds tremble, and so do I. 11.24 I am shaken to my innermost core, having seen You touch the sky, blazing, multicoloured, with your mouth wide open and enormous fiery eyes. I can find neither courage nor tranquillity, O Viá¹£á¹‡u! 11.25 And having seen Your mouths and formidable tusks glowing like fires of universal destruction, I have lost my bearings, nor do I find comfort. Have mercy Lord of gods, universal abode! 11.26 All these sons of Dhá¹›itarÄá¹£á¹­ra and the hosts of kings, BhÄ«á¹£ma, Droá¹‡a and Kará¹‡a are there in the distance, as well as our chief warriors, 11.27 hurriedly disappearing into Your frightening mouths with formidable tusks. Some can still be seen clinging between Your teeth with crushed heads. 11.28 As a multitude of torrents and rivers flow towards the ocean, so do the heroes of the world of men stream into your flaming mouths. 11.29 As moths swiftly fly into a blazing flame courting destruction, so also do they, hurtling towards annihilation, enter into Your mouths. 11.30 You lick up entire worlds, devouring them from all sides with flaming mouths. O Viá¹£á¹‡u, Your fierce rays blaze forth, filling the whole universe with brilliance.Â 11.31 Tell me who You are, with such a terrifying appearance. I salute You. Have mercy, O greatest of divinities! I wish to know You, O primeval One. I do not understand what You are doing.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 11.32 â€˜I am Time, the mighty cause of the destruction of the world, arisen here to annihilate the universe. Even without you, all these warriors who are arrayed in opposing ranks will cease to exist. 11.33 They have already been struck down by Me. Just be the instrument, Arjuna. Stand up and attain fame! Enjoy prosperous kingship having conquered the enemy. 11.34 Droá¹‡a, BhÄ«á¹£ma, Jayadratha, Kará¹‡a and also the others warrior heroes have already been killed by Me. Slay them! Do not hesitate! Fight! You shall conquer the enemy in battle.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">SaÃ±jaya said, 11.35 â€˜On hearing this from Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, Arjuna prostrated himself again and again with folded hands, shaking and terrified, bowing down, he spoke fearfully to Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a with a stutter.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 11.36 â€˜O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, of course the universe rejoices and delights in Your renown. Terrified demons flee in all directions and whole throngs of perfected sages bow down to you. 11.37Â And why should they not bow to You as the very first creator, O magnificent One, greater even than BrahmÄ! You are the home of the universe, O infinite Lord of gods, imperishable, beyond both existence and non-existence. 11.38 You are the very first divinity, the ancient Spirit. You are the ultimate resting place of this entire universe. You are the knower, the object of knowledge and the supreme state. The whole universe is pervaded by You, O One of infinite forms. 11.39 You are the wind, death, fire and the oceans, the moon, the progenitor and great-grandfather. I salute You a thousand times and salute again. I bow to You, over and over again! 11.40Â I bow to You from in front and from behind, I revere You everywhere too, O Everything. You pervade all, therefore You are the All. You are of infinite valour and boundless might. 11.41 When I impetuously thought of You as â€˜my friendâ€™ when I called you â€˜Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, son of Yadu, brotherâ€™ through ignorance of Your Lordliness, through negligence or even out of affection, 11.42 and when You were disrespectfully treated with humorous intent while at play, in bed, while seated, while eating or when alone, O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, or even in front of others, for that I ask forgiveness of You, O immeasurable One. 11.43 You are the father of the world, of everything animate and inanimate. You are adored by this world, You, the most venerable Guru. There is no one better or even like You in the three worlds, how then in another, O incomparable Being? 11.44 Therefore I bow down, prostrating my body. I beg forgiveness of Your Lordship.Â I offer praise as a son to his father, a friend to a friend or a lover to the beloved. O divine One, be merciful!Â 11.45 Having seen that which has never been seen I am overjoyed and yet my heart is throbbing with fear. Just show me that previous form, O divine One. Have mercy Lord of gods, refuge of the universe. 11.46 I wish to see you as before, wearing a diadem with club and discus in hand. O thousand-armed One, reassume that four-armed shape, O You of many forms.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 11.47 â€˜I have graced you with the manifestation of this Supreme form through My own power, O Arjuna. This is My universal, infinite and original splendour, which has never before been seen by anyone but you. 11.48 I cannot be seen in such a form in the world of men by any other but you, O Arjuna, not by Vedic sacrifices, incantations, gifts, ritual acts or even severe austerities. 11.49 You should not tremble or be bewildered on seeing such a terrible form of Mine as this one. Behold My previous form with a cheerful heart and be free of fear once again.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">SaÃ±jaya said, 11.50 â€˜After speaking to Arjuna like this Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a once again revealed his own form. Having become gentle and handsome once more, the mighty One calmed down his terrified friend.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 11.51 â€˜Seeing Your gentle human form Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, now I am composed. My heart has been restored to its natural state.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 11.52 â€˜This form of Mine which you have seen is extremely difficult to behold. Even the gods are constantly vying to see this expression.11.53 I cannot be seen in the way you have beheld Me by means of scriptural study, charitable giving, spiritual practices or even rituals. 11.54 Only through pure devotion can I be seen and known thus Arjuna, and truly attained. 11.55 Whoever carries out My work, who regards Me as the Supreme goal, devoted to Me, free from attachment and feeling no hostility to any creature, O Arjuna, he comes to Me.â€™</span></p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â What is being referred to here, are heaven, earth and the space between them.</span></p>','images/music/file/416779789.mp3',''),(63,12,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XII</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Yoga of Devotion</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna asked, 12.1 â€˜Which devotees, who are constant and steadfast, have a better understanding of yoga: those who worship You or those who worship the indestructible and the unmanifest?â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied,12.2 â€˜Those who fix their mind on Me, ever steadfast, who worship Me endowed with supreme faith, theyÂ are regarded by Me to be better qualified.Â 12.3Â But those who contemplate that which is indestructible, indefinable, unmanifest, all-pervading, unthinkable, unchanging, unshakeable and unmoving;Â 12.4 restraining the various senses and always unwavering in reason, they also reach Me, rejoicing in the welfare of all beings. 12.5Â The hardship is far greater for those who fix their minds on the unmanifest.Â The unmanifest goal is really difficult to reach for embodied beings.Â 12.6Â But those who surrender all actions to Me, worshipping Me as Supreme, meditating on Me in undivided union, 12.7Â fixing their minds on Me, O Arjuna, I soon become their liberator from the ocean of death and transmigration.Â 12.8 Focus your mind solely on Me. Fix your intellect on Me and no doubt you will soon abide in Me alone. 12.9Â But if you cannot constantly fix your mind on Me then seek to reach Me by the yoga of repeated practice, O Arjuna.Â 12.10Â If you are unable to practice even this, let your actions be dedicated to Me as Supreme. You will also attain perfection if you perform actions for My sake.Â 12.11Â Although seeking refuge in Me, if you are unable to do even this, then act with self-restraint, letting go of the results of all actions. 12.12Â In fact, knowledge is more refined than repeated efforts; meditation is superior to knowledge and renunciation of the result of action to meditation. From detachment, peace arises instantly. 12.13Â Friendly and even compassionate towards all creatures, without hatred; free from selfishness and lacking in ego; indifferent to pleasure or pain and patient,Â 12.14Â a yogin is ever content, self-controlled and unwavering with mind and reason fixed in Me. Whoever is devoted to Me, that one is dear to Me.Â 12.15Â Whoever is not afflicted by the world and does not afflict the world, who is free from elation, impatience, fear and agitation, that one is dear to Me.Â 12.16The person who is devoted to Me is desireless, pure, careful, impartial, free from stress; shunning all materialism, that one is dear to Me.Â 12.17Â Whoever is not elated, nor hateful, neither grieving nor craving, detached from the pleasant and the unpleasant is full of devotion. That one is dear to Me. 12.18Â Treating enemies and friends equally and similarly honour or disgrace; for whom heat or cold and pleasure or pain are the same, that one is free from attachment.Â 12.19 That person is dear to Me who, when faced with blame or praise remains neutral, quiet and contented with anything whatsoever, feeling homeless</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, unperturbed and full of devotion.Â 12.20 Those who honour this timeless practice as described here, keeping faith in Me as the Supreme, they are my devotees. They are exceedingly dear to Me.â€™</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> There can be, and there usually is, a strong attachment to oneâ€™s home. As the Self is oneâ€™s true home, the attitude should be one of <i>feeling homelessÂ </i>in the material sense.</span></p>','images/music/file/776311832.mp3',''),(64,13,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">XIII</span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Difference between Matter and Spirit</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 13.1 â€˜This body (and all matter) is called â€˜the fieldâ€™, O Arjuna.Â The wise refer to â€˜the knower of the fieldâ€™ as Spirit. 13.2 Know also, O Arjuna, that I am Spirit within all matter. I consider the understanding of the field and of the knower of the field to be true understanding. 13.3 What is this field and what is it like? What are its modifications and how do they arise? And who is Spirit, the knower of the field? What are Its powers? I shall explain this succinctly. 13.4 Sages have sung of Brahman in numerous different ways, in various sacred hymns, and even with clearly reasoned statements. 13.5 The great elements</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, ego, reason and the unmanifest</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, the senses, the ten and the one</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, as well as the five sense objects, 13.6 desire, hatred, pleasure, pain, the whole organism</span><a href=\"#_ftn4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, awareness and steadfastness briefly describe this field with its modifications. 13.7 Absence of pride, freedom from hypocrisy, non-violence, patience, honesty, purity, constancy, self-restraint, service to the teacher, 13.8 indifference to the objects of sense, absence of egoism, keeping in view the evils of birth, death and old age, of disease and pain; 13.9 non-attachment; not clinging to son, wife, home and the rest; and constant even-mindedness in the face of desirable and undesirable events; 13.10 unswerving devotion to Me with no other attachment;Â  frequenting secluded places, a distaste for crowds, 13.11 ever seeking spiritual knowledge and understanding the purpose of the knowledge of reality; all this is said to be wisdom. Anything other than this is ignorance. 13.12 I will describe what must be known to attain immortality, namely the beginningless, supreme Brahman, which is said to be neither being nor non-being. 13.13 It is present with hands and feet everywhere, eyes, heads and mouths everywhere, having ears in every direction. It pervades everything in the world. 13.14 Shining through the functions of all the senses, yet free from them; unattached yet sustaining all, free from the guá¹‡as</span><a href=\"#_ftn5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> yet enjoying them; 13.15 outside and within all beings, unmoving yet moving, incomprehensible because of its subtlety, far away yet near; 13.16 undivided and yet existing as if divided in all creatures, This is to be known as the sustainer of beings, their devourer and their creator. 13.17 That knowable Brahman is the light of lights and said to be beyond darkness. It is knowledge, that which is to be known and the goal of knowledge. It is seated in the hearts of all. 13.18 Thus, the field (matter), knowledge and that which is to be known have been briefly described.Â  Understanding this, My devotee gains access to My essence. 13.19 Know that praká¹›iti</span><a href=\"#_ftn6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, as well as Puruá¹£a</span><a href=\"#_ftn7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, are beginningless and also know that all consequent outcomes and qualities spring only from praká¹›iti. 13.20 Praká¹›iti is said to be the cause of the gross body and the agent of the sense instruments. In the experience of pleasure and pain, Puruá¹£a is said to be the cause.</span><a href=\"#_ftn8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> 13.21 Puruá¹£a abides in praká¹›iti enjoying the guá¹‡as emerging from praká¹›iti. Attachment to the guá¹‡as is the cause of births in good and evil wombs. 13.22 The highest Self in this body is called the witness, the permitter, the supporter, the experiencer, the great Lord and also the supreme Spirit. 13.23 Those who know Puruá¹£a and praká¹›iti in this way as well as the guá¹‡as, regardless of how they live, are not born again. 13.24 Some perceive the Self in the self by the self through meditation, others by SÄá¹…khya Yoga and still others through the path of action. 13.25 Yet some people, ignorant of this, worship having heard from others; they also cross beyond death through devotion to what they have heard. 13.26 O Arjuna, know that any being whatsoever, moving or unmoving, is born from the union of matter and Spirit. 13.27 He who sees the supreme Lord, existing equally in all beings, as the imperishable among the perishable, truly sees. 13.28 Because he sees the same Lord existing everywhere, he does not harm</span><a href=\"#_ftn9\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[9]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Himself with his mind. Thereby he goes to the supreme goal. 13.29 Whoever knows that all actions are performed exclusively by praká¹›iti and hence that the Self is not the doer, truly sees.Â 13.30 When he perceives the multifarious beings in existence as abiding in the One and proceeding from that One alone, he realises Brahman. 13.31 This imperishable Supreme Self, O Arjuna, being beginningless and beyond the guá¹‡as, neither acts nor is it tainted even though situated in the body.Â 13.32 As the all-pervading space is not polluted because of its subtlety, so the Self abiding everywhere in the body is not tainted. 13.33 As the sun alone lights up this whole world, so Spirit illumines all matter, O Arjuna. 13.34 Those who, through the eye of wisdom, perceive the distinction between the field (matter) and the knower of the field (Spirit), and the release of beings from praká¹›iti, go to the Supreme.â€™</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> In this case, these â€˜great elementsâ€™ refer to the subtle forms of earth, water, etc. that cannot be experienced by the senses.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> The unmanifest (nature) is the storehouse to which latent impressions are withdrawn at the end of a cosmic day. cf. 8.18 & 8.21</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">This refers to the five organs of knowledge (hearing, etc.); the five organs of action (speaking, handling, walking, excreting and procreating) and the mind.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> This refers to the body and the senses.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> <i>Guá¹‡a</i> generally means <i>quality</i>. Here it means <i>the three guá¹‡as</i>. <i>Sattva, rajas</i> and <i>tamas</i>, conducting, reflecting and absorbing consciousness.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><i>Praká¹›iti</i> is <i>nature</i> as in â€˜the <i>nature</i> of the universeâ€™, which functions through the three <i>guá¹‡as</i>, viz. <i>sattva, rajas</i> and <i>tamas</i>. Here <i>praká¹›iti</i> is called <i>the field/matter</i>.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> <i>Puruá¹£a</i> is Spirit or consciousness, the cause of the universe, here also called <i>the knower of the field</i>.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Spirit as consciousness enlivens the experience of pleasure and pain.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref9\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[9]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â Obviously, the Self cannot be harmed, but through ignoring the universal Self we reduce ourselves to limited individuals.</span></p>','images/music/file/1400455848.mp3',''),(65,14,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XIV</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The threeÂ guá¹‡as</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 14.1Â I shall again explain the highest and most excellent knowledge, having known which all the sages have escaped from this cycle of birth and death to supreme perfection. 14.2Â Resorting to this knowledge they have attained unity with Me. They are not born again on the manifestation of the world, neither do they tremble at its dissolution. 14.3Â My womb is the great Brahman. In it, I place the seed. That is the origin of all beings, O descendant of Bharata. 14.4Â Whatever forms are produced in any womb, O son of KuntÄ«, the great Brahman is their womb and I am the seed-sowing Father. 14.5Â Sattva, rajas and tamas are the guá¹‡as</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> existing in praká¹›iti. They bind the unchanging embodied Self to the body, O Arjuna. 14.6Â Sattva heals and gives light due to its purity. It binds through attachment to happiness and to knowledge, O sinless one. 14.7Â Know that rajas is of the nature of passion, giving rise to craving and attachment. It binds the embodied Self to action through attachment, O son of KuntÄ«. 14.8 But know tamas to be born of ignorance, deluding all embodied beings. It binds through negligence, laziness and sleep, O descendant of Bharata. 14.9 Sattva makes you attached to happiness, rajas binds you in action, O Arjuna, but, having obscured knowledge, tamas rather fetters you to negligence. 14.10Â Sattva arises having predominated over rajas and tamas, rajas over sattva and tamas, and likewise tamas over sattva and rajas, O BhÄrata. 14.11Â When the light of knowledge shines through all the gates of the body it indicates that sattva is predominant. 14.12Â Greed and craving, restlessness, initiation of activity andÂ exertion arise when rajas is predominant, O bull of the Bharatas. 14.13Â Lack of clarity, lethargy and negligence as well as delusion arise when tamas predominates, O joy of the Kuru clan. 14.14Â But if sattva is predominant at the moment of death, when the soul departs it enters pure worlds of the highest knowledge. 14.15Â If in rajas at death, it is reborn among those attached to action, and similarly dying in tamas, it returns into the wombs of the deluded. 14.16 Well-performed actions with a pure outcome are sÄttvika, but from rajas the outcome is misery and from tamas, ignorance. 14.17Â From sattva knowledge arises, from rajas greed and from tamas neglect, delusion and also ignorance. 14.18Â Those established in sattva go upwards, the rÄjasika types remain in the middle and the tÄmasika types go downwards and get stuck in the lowest guá¹‡a state</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. 14.19 When the observer is aware that no agent other than the guá¹‡as acts and knows that which is higher than the guá¹‡as, he attains My essence. 14.20Â Having transcended these three guá¹‡as which are the constituents of the body, an embodied being is released from birth, death, old age and pain, attaining immortality.â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna asked, 14.21 â€˜O Lord, what are the characteristics of one who has transcended these three guá¹‡as? What is their conduct like and how do they transcend these three guá¹‡as?â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 14.22 â€˜O Arjuna, he neither hates nor longs for the presence or absence of light (sattva), activity (rajas) or delusion (tamas).Â 14.23Â Undisturbed by the guá¹‡as, he is unmoved and settled as if indifferent, realising that It is all only the play of the guá¹‡as. 14.24 He for whom pleasure and pain are the same, who is steady in himself, to whomÂ mud, stone and gold are the same,Â with no preference towards loved ones or unloved ones, unaffected by blame and praise, 14.25Â equal in honour and dishonour, dispassionate toward friend or foe and who shuns any worldly pursuits, such a one is said to transcend the guá¹‡as. 14.26 And he who serves Me through the yoga of unswerving devotion, transcending these three guá¹‡as is ready to merge with Brahman. 14.27 For I am the abode of Brahman, immortal and unchanging, everlasting, the science of law and the one and only bliss.â€™</span></p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">In general, it means quality, but here it specifically refers to the three forces, the three states of consciousness.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">In this verse going upwards means being born as gods, remaining in the middle means having another human birth and going downwards means being born as an animal or a plant.Â </span></p>','images/music/file/397201612.mp3',''),(66,15,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XV</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Supreme Spirit</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 15.1 They speak of the eternal Peepal tree, its roots above and branches below, whose leaves are the Vedic hymns. Whoever knows this is well versed in the Vedas. 15.2 Nourished by the guá¹‡as, its extensive branches are below and above,</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> with sense-objects as shoots. And in the world of men below, it extends its roots and engenders action. 15.3 Its form</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> is not known here in this world, it has no beginning, end nor foundation. Having cut the well-established roots of this Peepal tree with the strong weapon of detachment, 15.4 that goal should be sought after, upon reaching which no one ever returns. I take refuge in that rudimental Spirit, from which the ancient current of saá¹sÄra flows. 15.5 Free from arrogance and delusion, having overcome the evils of attachment, their desires ineffective, free from the dualities known as pleasure and pain, ever dwelling in the Supreme Self, the clear-minded go towards that imperishable goal.Â 15.6 The sun does not shine there, nor does the moon, nor fire. Having gone there no one returns. That is My supreme abode. 15.7 A mere fragment of Myself becomes an eternal soul in the world of souls, drawing to itself the senses with the mind as the sixth, all existing in praká¹›iti. 15.8 The Lord acquires a body and later when he departs from it he takes away the senses and the mind, just as the wind carries away perfumes from their source. 15.9 He pursues sense objects using the ear, the eye, touch, taste and smell together with the mind. 15.10 The deluded do not recognize the One who is accompanied by the guá¹‡as, while living, enjoying or even dying. Those with the eye of knowledge understand. 15.11 Yogins who strive, perceive Him dwelling in the self. Unaware people, however, who also strive but who have not prepared themselves, do not perceive that One. 15.12 That brilliance which resides in the sun, which illumines the entire universe, which is in the moon and which is in fire, know that to be My brilliance. 15.13 Pervading the earth, I support every being with My energy and having become the watery moon, I nourish all the plants. 15.14 Having become the digestive fire of all men, I abide in the body of living beings. Associating with the vital and abdominal breath, I digest food in four ways</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. 15.15 I am seated in the hearts of all. From Me come memory and knowledge as well as their loss. I alone am known through all the Vedas, being the knower of their meaning and the teacher of the secrets of Vedanta. 15.16 There are these two entities in the world: the perishable and the imperishable. All beings are perishable. The unchanging is called the imperishable. 15.17 But distinct from these is the highest entity called The Supreme Self, the imperishable Lord, who pervades and supports the three worlds. 15.18 Since I transcend the perishable and am even beyond the imperishable creative principle, I am the Supreme Spirit, well known in the world and in the Vedas. 15.19 Whoever is never deceived, knowing Me thus as the Supreme Spirit, such an all-knowing one worships Me with his whole being, O son of BhÄrata. 15.20 I have thus expounded this most secret teaching, O Blameless One. Knowing this you will be wise and your duties will be fulfilled, O Son of BhÄrata.â€™</span></p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The illusory world or mÄyÄ is <i>below</i>. <i>Above</i> is the Brahman as its support.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">This whole verse is a description of ignorance, of saá¹sÄra: the never-ending cycle of births and deaths; and of its dissolution by detachment.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">As the food is chewed, swallowed, licked and sucked.</span></p>','images/music/file/529148860.mp3',''),(67,16,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XVI</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>Divine and Demonic Dispositions</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 16.1</span><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> â€˜Fearless, pure of heart, persevering in knowledge with applied practice, generous, self-restrained, devout, self-examining, disciplined and upright, 16.2Â non-violent, truthful, never angry, detached, peaceful, not indulging in slander, compassionate towards all beings, never envious, gentle, modest, not fickle, 16.3Â brilliant, patient, resilient, pure and clean, without malice and not unduly proud â€“ such people are born with divine tendencies, O BhÄrata. 16.4Â Hypocritical, arrogant, excessively proud, angry, harsh and ignorant people are born of a demonic tendency, O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ.</span><i><strong>Â </strong></i><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">16.5Â The divine disposition leads to liberation, the demonic one is known to lead to bondage. Do not be disheartened, O son of Paá¹‡á¸u! You were born with a divine disposition. 16.6 The two types of beings in this world are the divine and the demonic, the divine type has been explained in detail, now hear from Me about the demonic type, O Son of Pá¹›ithÄ. 16.7Â Demonic people do not understand when to engage in activity and when to disengage from activity. Neither purity nor good conduct nor truth is found in them. 16.8Â \"There is no truth in the universe,\" they say, \"it has no basis, there is no God, it is brought about randomly. What cause is there other than reproduction?â€ 16.9Â Holding such a view, these petty-minded, lost souls act cruelly, emerging as enemies of the world and causing its destruction. 16.10Â Wedded to insatiable desires, full of hypocrisy, arrogance and lust, and in the grip of lies due to delusion they act from impure resolutions. 16.11Â Beset with immeasurable anxiety until they die, for them gratification of desire is paramount, convinced that â€˜This is all there is.â€™ 16.12Â Bound by hundreds of snares of hope, dedicated to desire and anger, they seek to hoard wealth by unjust means for the gratification of their desires. 16.13Â â€˜Today I have acquired this.â€™ â€˜I shall fulfil that desire.â€™ â€˜This is mine and that wealth will also be mine.â€™ 16.14Â â€˜I have killed that enemy and I shall kill others too.â€™ â€˜I am the boss.â€™ â€˜I am the owner.â€™ â€˜I am successful, powerful and happy.â€™ 16.15Â â€˜I am rich and of noble birth.â€™ â€˜Is there anyone else like me?â€™ â€˜I will sacrifice, I will donate, I will have fun.â€™ Thinking thus, they are deluded by ignorance. 16.16Â Led astray by multiple imaginings, caught in a net of delusion and attached to the gratification of desires, they fall into a foul hell. 16.17Â They perform sacrifices in name only, fraudulently and not according to established rules; self-conceited, stubborn, filled with the arrogance and intoxication of wealth. 16.18 Clinging to ego, forceful, insolent, full of desire and anger, those resentful people despise the Self in their own body and in other bodies. 16.19 I perpetually hurl those cruel haters, wretches and impure beings into demonic wombs in the cycles of rebirth. 16.20 O Son of KuntÄ«, delusional people enter the wombs of demons. As they do not reach Me, birth after birth, they go from there to a lower state. 16.21Â The self-destructive, threefold gate to hell is this: lust, anger and greed. For this reason, this trio should be given up. 16.22Â O Son of KuntÄ«, avoiding these three gates of darkness, a man does what is best for himself and thus goes to the highest goal. 16.23 He who acts under the impulse of desire, ignoring scriptural injunctions, attains neither perfection nor happiness nor the highest goal. 16.24 Therefore, taking the scriptures as your authority on what should and should not be done and understanding the prescribed, scriptural injunctions, you can proceed here in this world.</span></p>','images/music/file/697681889.mp3',''),(68,17,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XVII</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>Threefold Faith</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 17.1 â€˜What is the situation of those who have cast aside scriptural injunctions, and yet worship full of faith, O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a? Is this due to sattva, rajas or tamas?â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 17.2 â€˜The faith of embodied beings is of three kinds, produced by their individual nature. It is either sÄttvika, rÄjasika or tÄmasika. Now listen. 17.3 Faith depends on the sattva in each person, O descendant of Bharata. A human being is full of faith and devotion. As you believe, so you are. 17.4 The sÄttvika worship the gods, the rÄjasika worship spirits and demons. The others, the tÄmasika types, worship the dead and hordes of ghostly spirits. 17.5 People who undergo extreme disciplines that are not enjoined by scriptures are full of deceit and egoism and driven by lust and attachment. 17.6 They mindlessly torture many of the organs within the body and even the Self embodied within. Know that these people have a demonic inclination. 17.7 Food that is dear to each being is also of three types. So too are sacrifices, disciplines and gifts. Listen now to the differences between them. 17.8 Foods that promote life, energy, strength, health, happiness and enjoyment, which are tasty, smooth, substantial and delicious are dear to the sÄttvika. 17.9 Foods that are bitter, sour, salty, excessively hot, pungent, dry and burning, which cause pain, grief and sickness, these the rÄjasika prefer. 17.10 Food which is stale, tasteless, putrid or impure; as well as leftovers and scraps are dear to the tÄmasika. 17.11 A sacrifice offered without a desire for any outcome, with the mind concentrated only on the need to offer, such a sacrifice which observes tradition, is sÄttvika. 17.12 But a sacrifice offered with a view to a reward, or also for show, know that to be rÄjasika, O best of the Bharatas. 17.13 A sacrifice that is contrary to tradition, performed without faith and without an offering of food, mantras or gifts, is regarded as tÄmasika. 17.14 Worship of gods, twice-born</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, teachers and the wise; purity, uprightness, chastity and non-violence, these are called disciplines of the body. 17.15 Speech that does not cause agitation, which is truthful, loving and beneficial, along with the practice of recitation is said to be the discipline of speech. 17.16 Serenity of mind, gentleness, silence, self-restraint and a very pure disposition, are called disciplines of the mind. 17.17 This threefold</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> discipline is regarded as sÄttvika when practised with the utmost faith by those who act appropriately and desire no result. 17.18 The display of discipline put onÂ merely to obtain honour, respect and reverence is called rÄjasika, as it is unstable and transitory. 17.19 Discipline practised under ignorance is called tÄmasika. It inflicts pain on oneself or has the aim of harming another. 17.20 A gift which is due to a worthy person, given at the proper place and time without any expectations, that gift is considered sÄttvika. 17.21 But a gift given with the aim of returning a favour or looking for a reward, or which is given grudgingly, that gift is considered to be rÄjasika. 17.22 That gift given to those who are unworthy, in the wrong place and at the wrong time, arrogantly or without respect, is called tÄmasika. 17.23Â à¥Â TAT SAT</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> is the threefold indication by which Brahman is remembered. Since ancient times the BrÄhmaá¹‡as, the Vedas and sacrifices have been structured based on this. 17.24 Therefore, the followers of Brahman always begin acts of sacrifice, offerings and disciplines by uttering the syllableÂ à¥, as prescribed by tradition. 17.25 Using the word TAT, those desiring liberation perform sacrifices and disciplines as well as various donation rituals, without looking for results. 17.26 The word SAT is used in the sense of reality and goodness. O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, SAT is also used in acts of praise. 17.27 Steadfastness in sacrifice, discipline and generosity is also called SAT. Likewise, SAT is action dedicated to the Lord. 17.28 Whatever gift is offered, or discipline is undertaken without faith is called ASAT, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, and counts for nothing in this world or the next.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">à¥ TAT SAT</span></p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> This refers to spiritually awakened people, not to those who have just been born physically.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> The threefold discipline of body, speech and mind described in verses 14, 15 and 16.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">à¥ is the sacred utterance that is recited at the beginning of any spiritual endeavour.Â à¤¤à¤¤à¥Â <i>TAT</i> Â is <i><strong>that</strong></i>Â (Brahman) andÂ à¤¸à¤¤à¥Â <i>SATÂ </i>Â is <i><strong>goodness,</strong></i> representing the <i><strong>Supreme Reality</strong></i>. â€˜OM. That Brahman is reality.â€™</span></p>','images/music/file/1604751984.mp3','images/qr/G68.png'),(69,18,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>XVIII</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Yoga of Liberation through Renunciation</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna asked, 18.1 â€™O mighty-armed one, I would like to know the real difference between renunciation and surrender.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 18.2 â€˜Sages understand renunciation to be the giving up of actions prompted by desire. The wise declare surrender to be the relinquishment of the outcome of all action. 18.3 Some men of wisdom declare that action is to be abandoned and is evil; but according to others acts of sacrifice, charity and spiritual discipline are not to be given up. 18.4 O best of Bharatas, hear My thoughts on surrender. O tiger among men, surrender is said to be of three kinds: 18.5 Acts of sacrifice, charity, and spiritual discipline should be performed, not abandoned; since sacrifice, generosity and spiritual discipline are indeed purifying for the wise. 18.6 However, even these actions should be performed without claiming the results, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, this is My definite and ultimate belief. 18.7 However, renouncing obligatory action is not right; its abandonment due to delusion is said to be tÄmasika. 18.8 He who abandons painful actions from mere fear of physical hardship performs rÄjasika surrender. He does not obtain any benefit from such surrender. 18.9 When an action is done simply because it needs to be done while letting go of attachment to the outcome, O Arjuna, such surrender is deemed to be sÄttvika. 18.10 The wise man, filled with sattva, his doubt removed and practicing surrender, does not avoid disagreeable actions nor is he attached to agreeable ones. 18.11 Indeed, an embodied soul is not able to abandon actions entirely. But whoever surrenders the results of actions is said to be a proper renunciate. 18.12 After death, the threefold result of actions - desirable, undesirable or mixed - falls to those who have not surrendered the outcome, but never to renunciates of desire-ridden action. 18.13 Learn from Me, O Arjuna, about these five aspects necessary for the accomplishment of all actions as described in SÄá¹…khya philosophy: 18.14 the seat of action (the causal, subtle and physical bodies), the actor (the enjoyer of the outcome of actions), different types of instruments, various functions (the five types of vital air, etc.) and divine consciousness, which is fifth among these. 18.15 Whatever action a man undertakes with his body, speech or mind, whether right or wrong, these are its five causal elements.Â 18.16 This being the case, he who sees the Self alone as the doer has an underdeveloped intelligence. Such a dimwit does not understand. 18.17 He who is free of any notion of ego, whose intellect is not tainted, even while killing these people he does not kill, nor is he bound. 18.18 Knowledge, what is known, and the knower form the threefold impulse for action. The instrument, the action and the doer are the threefold basis of action. 18.19 It is declared in SÄá¹…khyÄ philosophy that there are three kinds of knowledge, action and agent according to the different guá¹‡as. Now hear about these also. 18.20 That knowledge by which one sees one imperishable existence in all beings, undivided amongst the divided, know that as sÄttvika knowledge. 18.21 But that knowledge which sees all beings as separate and different, know that as rÄjasika knowledge. 18.22 However, that knowledge which is trivial and which gets stuck on one single issue as if it were the whole, without reason or real purpose, is said to be tÄmasika. 18.23 A regulated action, free from attachment, performed without desire or aversion, with no wish to obtain a result is said to be sÄttvika. 18.24 But an action performed with ego or with the wish to obtain a desired outcome, or even with a lot of exertion, that is said to be rÄjasika. 18.25 An action undertaken from delusion regardless of the consequences; disregarding loss, injury or competence, that is said to be tÄmasika. 18.26 A sÄttvika actor is free from attachment, unassuming, steadfast and enthusiastic, unperturbed by success or failure. 18.27 A rÄjasika actor is said to be passionate, desirous of the results of action, greedy, cruel, impure and subject to joy and sorrow. 18.28 A tÄmasika actor is said to be undisciplined, vulgar, obstinate, deceitful, vile, lazy, despondent and procrastinating. 18.29 Listen, O Arjuna, as the three divisions of understanding and of steadfastness are explained in full detail according to the guá¹‡as. 18.30 That intellect is sÄttvika which understands when to participate and when to withdraw, what should and what should not be done, when to be afraid and when to be fearless and the difference between bondage and liberation, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ. 18.31 That intellect is rÄjasika which distinguishes incorrectly between right and wrong and confuses that which should be done with that which should not be done, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ. 18.32 That intellect, enveloped in darkness, which thinks that wrong is right and gets everything back to front, is tÄmasika. 18.33 The unswerving firmness with which one regulates the functions of the mind, the vital breath and the senses through yoga, that steadfastness is sÄttvika, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ. 18.34 But, O Arjuna, the firmness with which one clings to duty, pleasure and wealth, while attached to and desirous of results, that steadfastness is rÄjasika. 18.35 That firmness, O son of Pá¹›ithÄ, by which a fool is stuck in a dreamworld, in fear, grief, depression and conceit is tÄmasika. 18.36 And now listen O Arjuna, to My description of the threefold happiness and how through practice one enjoys life and reaches the end of misery. 18.37 That which feels like poison at first but later transforms into nectar, that happiness is declared to be sÄttvika, arising from the tranquillity of ones own mind. 18.38 That happiness is considered to be rÄjasika which arises from sense contact with objects, and which at first resembles nectar but later transforms into poison. 18.39 That happiness arising from sleep, idleness and carelessness, deluding oneself both in the beginning and afterwards, is called tÄmasika. 18.40 No being exists who is free from these three guá¹‡as generated by nature, neither on earth nor even in heaven among the gods. 18.41 Arjuna, the actions of BrÄhmaá¹‡as, Ká¹£atriyas, VaiÅ›yas and ÅšÅ«dras</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> are distributed according to the qualities inherent in their own nature. 18.42 BrÄhmaá¹‡as naturally practise control of body and mind, spiritual discipline, purity, patience, uprightness, knowledge, wisdom and piety. 18.43 Ká¹£atriyas are naturally drawn to heroism, power, firmness, shrewdness, generosity, leadership and do not run away from a fight. 18.44 VaiÅ›yas are naturally drawn to agriculture, cattle-herding and commerce. ÅšÅ«dras are necessarily drawn towards activities of hired labourers. 18.45 A man attains perfection when he delights in his own work</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">. Hear then how someone, content with his own mission in life, finds fulfilment. 18.46 Human beings find fulfilment through dedicating their own work to a higher cause, to that One from whom all beings originate and by whom all this is pervaded. 18.47 Better to do oneâ€™s own duty badly than to do someone elseâ€™s duty well.</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0, 0%, 0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â Performing actions prescribed by ones own nature, one cannot go wrong. 18.48 O Arjuna, one should not abandon the work to which one is born, even if poorly executed. Indeed, all undertakings are surrounded by shortcomings as fire by smoke. 18.49 With a detached intellect in all situations, having conquered the ego, one who is free from desire attains the Supreme through surrender, perfectly uninvolved in doership. 18.50 O Arjuna, I will explain succinctly how one who reaches perfection also attains Brahman, which is the highest state of wisdom. 18.51 Endowed with a pure intellect and firmly self-controlled, no longer getting stuck on sounds and other sense objects, rejecting attraction and repulsion, 18.52 dwelling in solitude, eating lightly, controlling speech, body and mind, constantly focussing and engaging in meditation, resorting to detachment, 18.53 having given up selfishness, dominance, arrogance, desire, anger and greed, free from the notion of â€˜mineâ€™; that one is tranquil and ready to merge with Brahman. 18.54 Attuned to Brahman with a serene mind, neither grieving nor desiring, the same towards all beings, that one gains My supreme love. 18.55 Devoted to Me, he recognizes who and what I am in essence. Then, knowing My essence, he merges with Me instantly. 18.56 Ever trusting in Me while performing all actions, by My grace he reaches the eternal, unchanging destination. 18.57 Having consciously offered up all actions to Me, regarding Me as Supreme, resorting to mental concentration, let your mind always rest on Me. 18.