an class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>III</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>The Path of Action</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 3.1 â€˜If you are convinced that knowledge is better than action, O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, why do you urge me to take part in such savage deeds?Â  3.2 You confuse my reason with what appears to be a perplexing statement. Tell me this once and for all: how may I attain the Ultimate?â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 3.3 â€˜O Arjuna, Since ancient times I have proclaimed a twofold path for this world: The path of knowledge for yogins</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> following SÄá¹…khyÄ</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> and the path of action for action-oriented people.Â  3.4 Man does not achieve freedom from action by avoiding activity. Nor will he reach perfection by mere renunciation. 3.5 In fact no one has ever existed, without performing action even for a moment. The guá¹‡as which are generated from praká¹›iti</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> force everyone to be active even against their will. 3.6 One who sits restraining his organs of action,</span><a href=\"#_ftn4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> while confused and brooding in his mind over sense-objects, is a hypocrite. 3.7 But, Arjuna, better is a yogin who controls his senses with his mind, his organs of action unattached, although starting out on the path of action. 3.8 Do your allotted duty.Â Action is certainly better than non-action. Even the maintenance of your body requires action. 3.9 Unless they perform actions as an offering</span><a href=\"#_ftn5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">, everyone in this world is bound by actions. O Son of KuntÄ«, act in this way, free from attachment. 3.10 In the beginning, having created mankind through sacrifice, the Creator said,Â  â€˜Produce in this way. May this be your wish-fulfilling cow.â€™</span><a href=\"#_ftn6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> 3.11 â€˜By this sacrifice may you nourish the gods; may those gods nourish you. By nourishing one another, you will attain the highest welfare.â€™Â  3.12 The gods, fed by sacrifice will indeed give you your desired delights. But who enjoys these gifts without giving back to the gods, is indeed a thief. 3.13 Good people who eat what remains from the sacrifice are freed from all sins. But those sinners, who cook and eat for themselves</span><a href=\"#_ftn7\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[7]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> alone, consume only wrongdoing. 3.14 Beings come from food, food is produced by rain, rain comes from sacrifice and sacrifice originates from right action. 3.15 Know that ritualistic action arises from the creator and spiritual knowledge arises from the Imperishable. This is why the all-pervading Brahman is ever upheld by dedicated actions. 3.16 O Son ofÂ Pá¹›ithÄ, whoever here on earth does not turn with the wheel of sacrifice but only enjoys sensual pleasures is causing harm. He lives in vain. 3.17 On the other hand for people who delight only in the Self, who are satisfied in the Self and are content in the Self alone, there is no duty. 3.18 He has nothing to gain in this world from doing work or leaving work undone. Nor does he depend on any creature for any particular outcome. 3.19 Therefore always perform necessary actions without attachment. For when someone performs actions with detachment that person attains the Supreme. 3.20 King Janaka and others attained perfection through action alone. You too should act likewise, looking to the worldâ€™s welfare. 3.21 However a great person behaves, so too will others. Whatever standard he sets is what people will follow. 3.22 O Arjuna, there is nothing whatsoever for Me to accomplish in the three worlds, nor anything outstanding that has to be attained. Yet I still engage in action. 3.23 In fact, if I did not engage tirelessly in action, even for a moment, mankind would follow my lead, O son ofÂ Pá¹›ithÄ. 3.24 These worlds would perish if I did not continue to act. I would destroy these creatures and cause confusion. 3.25 Descendant of Bharata, just as ignorant people act due to their attachment to action, so the wise should act without attachment, desiring only to sustain the world. 3.26 Do not allow the minds of the ignorant to be disturbed, as they are attached to action. The wise, holding to discipline, should allow everyone to enjoy action. 3.27 In any case, actions are done by the guá¹‡as of praká¹›iti. Confused by egoism someone imagines \"I am the doer.\" 3.28 But, mighty-armed Arjuna, he who knows the truth about the parts played by the senses</span><a href=\"#_ftn8\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[8]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> and by action, thinks, The senses work among sense objects,\" and such a one remains detached. 3.29 Whoever is deluded about the guá¹‡as of praká¹›iti is attached to the activity of the guá¹‡as. Whoever understands this fully should not disturb the ignorant whose knowledge is incomplete. 3.30 Offer up all actions to Me. Meditate on the transcendent. Be free from desire. Be free from selfishness and when your fever is gone, FIGHT! 3.31 People who continually practise this teaching of Mine faithfully and without grumbling are also released from this sense of doership. 3.32 But they are lost and mindless who dismiss My teaching and do not practice it. You should realise that they are confused about all this knowledge. 3.33 Even the wise act in accordance with their own nature. Beings follow their nature. What then will restraint accomplish? 3.34 Repulsion and attraction toward sense-objects are seated in the senses. One should not come under the dominion of attraction and repulsion; they are the real enemy. 3.35 Better to do oneâ€™s own duty badly than to do someone elseâ€™s duty well. Better to die doing your own duty. The duty of another invites danger.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 3.36Â â€˜O Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a, by what then is a man impelled to commit such grave errors,Â even against his will, as if by force?â€™Â </span></p><p styl