Upaniá¹£ads)</strong></i></span><i><strong> </strong></i><span style=\"color:#385623;\"><i><strong>in a conversation betweenÂ </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#FF6600;\"><i><strong>ÅšrÄ« Ká¹›iá¹£á¹‡a</strong></i><strong>Â </strong></span><span style=\"color:black;\"><i><strong>andÂ </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#CC0099;\"><i><strong>Arjuna</strong></i></span><i><strong> on </strong></i><span style=\"color:#525252;\"><i><strong>the Science ofÂ </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#00B0F0;\"><i><strong>the Supreme Spirit</strong></i></span><i><strong> and </strong></i><span style=\"color:#C00000;\"><i><strong>the Art ofÂ </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#0070C0;\"><i><strong>Self-Knowledge,</strong></i></span><i><strong> here endsÂ </strong></i><span style=\"color:#00B050;\"><i><strong>theÂ </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#7030A0;\"><i><strong>third </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#806000;\"><i><strong>chapter</strong></i></span><i><strong> </strong></i><span style=\"color:#00B050;\"><i><strong>entitled</strong></i></span><i><strong> </strong></i><span style=\"color:#7030A0;\"><i><strong>the Path ofÂ </strong></i></span><span style=\"color:#CC0099;\"><i><strong>Action.</strong></i></span></p>','images/music/file/2095500670.mp3',''),(594,4,0,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>IV</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"><strong>Renunciation of Action through Knowledge</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord said, 4.1 â€˜I proclaimed this imperishable yoga to Vivasvat. Vivasvat communicated it to Manu, and Manu imparted it to Iká¹£vÄku. 4.2 When the royal sages received it, they understood it and passed it down. After a long time here on earth this yoga has been lost, O Scorcher of Foes. 4.3 Today I am passing this ancient yoga on to you since you are My devotee and friend. This indeed is the ultimate secret.â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Arjuna said, 4.4 â€˜As the birth of Vivasvat was much earlier on than your birth, how should I understand, that you proclaimed this in the beginning?â€™Â </span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">The Blessed Lord replied, 4.5 â€˜Just like you, Arjuna, I have had many births. I know them all, but you do not remember any, O scorcher of foes. 4.6 Though I Myself am unborn and imperishable, I recreate Myself by the power of illusion. Being the Lord of all beings, I rule over My own praká¹›iti.</span><a href=\"#_ftn1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> 4.7 I manifest Myself, whenever there is a decline in righteousness and injustice prevails, O descendant of Bharata. 4.8 I am reborn from age to age for the sake of re-establishing justice, for the preservation of the good and the destruction of evil-doers. 4.9Â Whoever realises the truth about My divine birth and action, does not take another birth having left this embodiment. He comes to Me, O Arjuna. 4.10 Purified by the discipline of knowledge, freed from greed, fear and anger, thinking only of Me and taking refuge in Me, many have attained My being.Â  4.11Â In whatever way they approach Me, I reward them. O Arjuna, people follow My path in many ways. 4.12Â People worship certain powers longing for success through their actions. Here, in this world mundane actions meet with success very quickly indeed. 4.13 The system of the four castes</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> was created by Me, according to the distribution of guá¹‡as and activities. Although I am the agent of this system, you should know Me as the eternal non-doer,Â 4.14 actions do not bind Me as I do not crave results. Whoever understands Me in this way, is not bound by action. 4.15 This was known in days of old, even the ancient seekers of liberation performed actions. That is why you should carry out actions just as they did in antiquity. 4.16 â€˜What is action? What is inaction?â€™ Even the wise are confused about this! I will explain action to you, understanding which, you will be freed from harm. 4.17 You need to know about duties as well as forbidden actions, and also understand inaction. The way of action is profound. 4.18 Whoever perceives inaction in action and action in inaction, is wise among men. That one is a yogin, the performer of all action. 4.19 Whoever has excluded desire and expectation from all his dealings and has burnt up his actions in the fire</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> of knowledge, the wise call a sage. 4.20 Having surrendered attachment to results, ever contented and independent, he does nothing at all although fully engaged in action. 4.21 No harm can come to him as he has no expectations, restrained in thought and self-controlled, having surrendered any sense of ownership and with his body alone performing actions. 4.22 Content with whatever comes, rising above the pairs of opposites, free from envy, the same in success and in failure, even though he is acting he is not bound. 4.23 Free from attachment, liberated, his mind established in true knowledge, he performs all actions as an offering leaving no trace. 4.24 The offering</span><a href=\"#_ftn4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> is consciousness, the oblation is consciousness, poured out by consciousness into the fire of consciousness. Brahman is to be attained by him alone who is fully absorbed in consciousness while acting.</span><a href=\"#_ftn5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> 4.25 Some yogins perform sacrifices only to the gods; others offer sacrifice through dedication itself in the fire of the Supreme reality. 4.26 Some offer the senses such as hearing in the fire of restraint. Others offer sound and other sense objects in the fire of sense perception. 4.27 Others offer all the actions of the senses and the functions of the vital breath in the fire of the Yoga of self-control, kindled by wisdom. 4.28 Some offer material possessions or physical disciplines, others dedicate Yoga practice, while ascetics of severe vows offer up their study of the scriptures and self-knowledge. 4.29 Others offer the incoming breath into the outgoing breath, and the outgoing breath into the incoming breath, restraining the flow of inhalation and exhalation, intent on controlling the vital breath. 4.30 Others, restricting their diets, offer their vital breath into the vital breath. All of them know about dedicating action and also that sacrifice dissolves bad habits. 4.31 Those who enjoy the immortal nectar, the remnant of sacrifice, go to the eternal Brahman. This world is not for those who do not offer up their actions, how then any other world, O Best of Kurus? 4.32 Thus, offerings of many kinds are presented to Brahman. Know them all to be the result of activity. Understand this and you will be free. 4.33 Scorcher of foes, offering up wisdom is better than offering up material possessions. O Arjuna, all action without exception, culminates in wisdom. 4.34 Know that the wise, seers of truth, will initiate you into Self-knowledge through your humble submission, enquiry and service. 4.35 Knowing that, you will not turn to delusion again, O Arjuna.Â Then you will see all beings in yourself, as well as in Me. 4.36 Even if you are the most sinful of all evildoers, you will transcend all wickedness by the raft of knowledge. 4.37 As a blazing fire reduces firewood to ashes, O Arjuna, so does the fire of knowledge reduce all seeds of action to ashes. 4.38 There is really nothing more purifying than wisdom. In time, whoever perfects himself through yoga will find Himself. Â 4.39 Endowed with faith one acquires knowledge. Devoted to this, one restrains the senses. Having found wisdom, one soon attains supreme peace. 4.40 Whoever is ignorant, lacking in faith or who has a doubting personality is ruined. Those of a doubting nature find no happiness either now in this world or in the future. 4.41 Action is not binding for someone who is self-aware, O Arjuna. He acts with indifference</span><a href=\"#_ftn6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> because of yoga and his doubts are uprooted by knowledge. 4.42 Therefore, with your own sword of knowledge slash the doubts that have been produced by the ignorance lodged in your heart. Resort to Yoga! Get up, Arjuna!â€™</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â </p><p><br>Â </p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[1]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> material nature</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><a href=\"#_ftnref2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> According to their nature some people are more inclined to spend their time either in hired labour, often physical, (Å›udra) or as merchants and farmers (vaiÅ›ya), as rulers (ká¹£atriya), or discovering the Brahman (brÄhmaá¹‡a). If this is decided through birth and surname, rather than allowing each person to express their own nature, it gives the caste system a bad name. This verse clearly states that it depends on theÂ guá¹‡a balance and that it is activity-based. cf. 18.41-43</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><a href=\"#_ftnref3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> In this metaphor, <strong>fire</strong> has the function of burning away long-lasting impressions from past actions, which are lodged in the heart through spiritual practices. <strong>Fire</strong> has the same meaning in verses 26, 27 and 37.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><a href=\"#_ftnref4\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[4]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">Â For most religious practitioners the fire sacrifice, what is put into the fire, to whom it is dedicated, the aim, the performance of it, the priest and the instruments used, are all different. For the Yogin they are all Brahman, i.e. consciousness. (One of the four great statements from the Upanishad is <i><strong>prajÃ±Änaá¹ƒ brahma</strong></i>, meaning consciousness is Brahman.) For a fire sacrifice the agent is the priest as he performs the sacrifice; the clarified butter is the object; the ladle with which the clarified butter is poured into the fire is the instrument, the intention is some favourable outcome, the fire is the centre of the ceremony, the location. In this verse all are seen as consciousness.Â </span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref5\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[5]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> How is this relevant to us? Do we not all have our daily rituals that we practice to obtain specific results? For example, brushing our teeth or eating. When we eat, we make offerings to the digestive fire in our stomach; therefore, this verse is often chanted before meals.</span></p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref6\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[6]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> Indifference here implies freedom from being driven by desire, but not carelessness.</span></p>','images/music/file/554715609.mp3',''),(595,4,1,'<p><span style=\"color:#FF6600;\"><strong>à¤¶à¥à¤°à¥€à¤­à¤—à¤µà¤¾</strong></span><span style=\"color:#806000;\"><strong>à¤¨à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤š</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"color:#806000;\"><strong>à¤‡à¤®à¤‚</strong></span><span style=\"color:black;\"><strong>Â </strong></span><span style=\"color:#0070C0;\"><strong>à¤µà¤¿à¤µà¤¸à¥à¤µà¤¤à¥‡</strong></span><span style=\"color:black;\"><strong>Â </strong></span><span style=\"color:red;\"><strong>à¤¯à¥‹à¤—à¤‚ -Â </strong></span><span style=\"color:#833C0B;\"><strong>à¤ªà¥à¤°à¥‹à¤•à¥à¤¤à¤µà¤¾à¤¨</strong></span><span style=\"color:#FF6600;\"><strong>à¤¹à¤®</strong></span><span style=\"color:#00B050;\"><strong>à¤µà¥à¤¯à¤¯à¤®