ion of action. 5.3 O Mighty Armed One, whoever neither craves nor detests anything is known as a true renunciate; indifferent to these pairs of opposites, he is easily liberated from bondage. 5.4 Immature people say that SÄá¹…khya</span><a href=\"#_ftn2\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[2]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> and yoga are different, but not so the wise. Adhering fully to just one of these, the result of both is achieved. 5.5 The state attained by SÄá¹…â€khyas is also reached by karma yogins. Whoever perceives that SÄá¹…â€khya and yoga are one, understands clearly. 5.6 However, Arjuna, renunciation is difficult to achieve without yoga. The earnest seeker, well-practised in yoga, attains Brahman after a short while. 5.7 The competent Yogin who has purified his mind, subdued his ego and mastered his senses, his self, having become the Self of all beings, is not tainted although acting. 5.8 An accomplished knower of truth would think, \"I do nothing</span><a href=\"#_ftn3\"><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\">[3]</span></a><span class=\"text-huge\" style=\"color:hsl(0,0%,0%);font-family:Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;\"> at all,\" while seeing, hearing, touching, smelling, eating, walking, sleeping, breathing, 5.9 talking, evacuating, using his hands; opening or shutting the eyes. He is convinced that â€˜it is only the senses that move among sense-objectsâ€™. 5.10 Dedicating his actions to the Self, having let go of attachments, he is not tainted by wrong action, just as water does not stick to a lotus leaf. 5.11 For fully detached yogins, only the body, mind, reason and senses perform action, for self-purification. 5.12 Competent seekers, having relinquished the outcome of action, attain complete peace. The incompetent, attached to results and driven by desire, a