is undisturbed by heat or cold, pleasure and pain, even by honour and disgrace. 6.8Â That yogin is said to be realised who is satisfied in self-knowledge, who is discerning and immovable and whose senses are under control. For him gold, stone and a lump of clay have the same value. 6.9 Whoever has equal regard for friends or enemies, family, impartial or indifferent people, the kind-hearted or quarrelsome, just or unjust,Â he is special. 6.10 A yogin should steady his mind continually, remaining in solitude, alone, mastering mind and body, free from expectation and ownership. 6.11Â He should settle down on his own clean spot on a firm seat covered with kuÅ›a grass, cloth or fur which is neither too high nor too low. 6.12Â Sitting there on that seat, having made his mind single-pointed by controlling thought and the activity of the senses, he should practice yoga for self-purification. 6.13Â Motionless and firm, holding body, head and neck balanced, focussing on the tip of his nose and not glancing in any direction, 6.14Â his mind serene and fearless, firm in the vow of chastity, mentally in control, he should sit with his thoughts concentrated on Me as supreme. 6.15Â Thus, concentrating continually on the Self, the yogin whose mind is steady abides in Me and is free, having attained supreme peace. 6.16Â Yoga involves neither eating too much nor not eating at all, neither habitually sleeping too much, nor always staying awake O Arjuna. 6.17Â Yoga eliminates misery in a person who is moderate with food, leisure and work and also measured in sleep and wakefulness. 6.18Â When the mind is restrained and just rests in the Self, untouched by any desires one is then said to be in union. 6.19 As a candle placed in a windless spot does not flicker, neither does the controlled thought of a Yogin remain concentrated in union with the Self. 6.20Â When his unwavering mind is restrained by the practice of yoga and only contemplates the Self, he is contented in himself, 6.21Â he kn